Observations¶

  • Some of the higher chronically absent percentages drop quite a bit from 2018 to 2019
  • The hawaiian/pacific islander percentages are really strange, doesn't follow other trends
    • Could be fluctuation due to low numbers?
    • Maybe error in data collection?
    • Look into later
  • Across the years, none of the lines have really crossed each other except whatever is happening with hawaiian/pacific islander and one dip for native american students in 2019
    • African American students consistently have the highest percentage of chronic absence
    • Asians and Whites consistently have the lowest percentage of chronic absences
  • Mind that other factors besides inequality may affect these rates
    • Such as cultural emphasis on education
    • Possible changes or hiccups in data collection
  • Something weird is happening 2019
    • Everything dips by like 1%, maybe changes in data collection?
    • Use 2017-2018

state_2018 = att_state_all[ att_state_all["School Year"] == 2018]

def getCell(sg, column):
    return state_2018[state_2018["SubGroup"] == sg ][column].values[0]

absent_asian = getCell("Asian", "StudentsChronicallyAbsent")
total_asian = getCell("Asian", "Students")

absent_white = getCell("White", "StudentsChronicallyAbsent")
total_white = getCell("White", "Students")

absent_hl = getCell("Hispanic/Latino", "StudentsChronicallyAbsent")
total_hl = getCell("Hispanic/Latino", "Students")

absent_mr = getCell("Multi-Racial", "StudentsChronicallyAbsent")
total_mr = getCell("Multi-Racial", "Students")

absent_na = getCell("Native American", "StudentsChronicallyAbsent")
total_na = getCell("Native American", "Students")

absent_aa = getCell("African American", "StudentsChronicallyAbsent")
total_aa = getCell("African American", "Students")

#test_proportions_2indep(count1, nobs1, count2, nobs2, value=None, method=None, compare='diff', 
                        # alternative='two-sided', correction=True, return_results=True)
w_asian = smstats.proportion.test_proportions_2indep(absent_white, total_white, absent_asian, total_asian)
print("\nWhite - Asian")
print("Statistic: " + str(w_asian.statistic))
print("P-value: " + str(w_asian.pvalue))

w_hl = smstats.proportion.test_proportions_2indep(absent_white, total_white, absent_hl, total_hl)
print("\nWhite - Hispanic/Latino")
print("Statistic: " + str(w_hl.statistic))
print("P-value: " + str(w_hl.pvalue))

w_mr = smstats.proportion.test_proportions_2indep(absent_white, total_white, absent_mr, total_mr)
print("\nWhite - Multi-Racial")
print("Statistic: " + str(w_mr.statistic))
print("P-value: " + str(w_mr.pvalue))

w_na = smstats.proportion.test_proportions_2indep(absent_white, total_white, absent_na, total_na)
print("\nWhite - Native American")
print("Statistic: " + str(w_na.statistic))
print("P-value: " + str(w_na.pvalue))

w_aa = smstats.proportion.test_proportions_2indep(absent_white, total_white, absent_aa, total_aa)
print("\nWhite - African American")
print("Statistic: " + str(w_aa.statistic))
print("P-value: " + str(w_aa.pvalue))


# z = 12.062, p = 1.66 ^ -33, p very low, reject null hypothesis that there is no difference, is statistically significant
#print(absent_white, total_white, absent_hl, total_hl)

#ok, a better way of doing this
def printResult(r1, r2):
    absent_r1 = getCell(r1, "StudentsChronicallyAbsent")
    total_r1 = getCell(r1, "Students")
    absent_r2 = getCell(r2, "StudentsChronicallyAbsent")
    total_r2 = getCell(r2, "Students")
    result = smstats.proportion.test_proportions_2indep(absent_r1, total_r1, absent_r2, total_r2)
    print("\n"+r1 + " - " + r2)
    print("Statistic: " + str(result.statistic))
    print("P-value: " + str(result.pvalue))
    
printResult("Asian", "White")

    return state_2018[state_2018["SubGroup"] == sg ][column].values[0]

def printResult(r1, r2):
    do_r1 = getCell(r1, "Dropouts")
    total_r1 = getCell(r1, "Students")
    do_r2 = getCell(r2, "Dropouts")
    total_r2 = getCell(r2, "Students")
    result = smstats.proportion.test_proportions_2indep(do_r1, total_r1, do_r2, total_r2)
    print("\n"+r1 + " - " + r2)
    print("Statistic: " + str(result.statistic))
    print("P-value: " + str(result.pvalue))

printResult("White", "Multi-Racial")
printResult("White", "African American")
printResult("White", "Hispanic/Latino")

def getCell(sg, column, df):
    return df[df["SubGroup"] == sg ][column].values[0]

def printResult(df, r1, r2):
    part_r1 = getCell(r1, "AvgNumTargetMet",df)
    total_r1 = getCell(r1, "Students",df)
    part_r2 = getCell(r2, "AvgNumTargetMet",df)
    total_r2 = getCell(r2, "Students",df)
    result = smstats.proportion.test_proportions_2indep(part_r1, total_r1, part_r2, total_r2)
    print("\n"+r1 + " - " + r2)
    print("Statistic: " + str(result.statistic))
    print("P-value: " + str(result.pvalue))

print("Using an alpha level of .05 : ")
print("Not statistically significant, unable to reject the null hypothesis that the two proportions are equal:")
printResult(growth_ela,"White", "Multi-Racial")
printResult(growth_ela,"White", "Native American")

print("\nStatistically significant, the two proportions are different:")
printResult(growth_ela,"White", "Asian")
printResult(growth_ela,"White", "Hispanic/Latino")
printResult(growth_ela,"White", "African American")

print("\nUsing an alpha level of .05 : ")

Backtrack¶

  • Just realizing that average % of student growth acheived =/= average % of students meeting achieving the growth goal
  • Different from how the other datasets work
    • Not a proportion of how many student achieved / did not achieve the goal
    • Can't use proportion test
    • Actually an average, site says: "The average percent of student growth achieved statistic shows, on average, how close a group of students came to achieving their target."
    • I have the average, but not the standard dev of each subgroup, since I only have the summary data and they don't provide the standard dev??
  • Confused with how they're taking the average, no info given on this
    • Simpler to interpret with just percentage meeting / not meeting the goal
    • With an average though, it seemed like some grades had different scales of measurement than others?
    • Reference to Delaware Success Framework: https://www.doe.k12.de.us/cms/lib/DE01922744/Centricity/Domain/310/Delaware%20School%20Success%20Framework%20Reference%20Document-Updated12.15-1.26.pdf
    • Mentioned growth was out of 225 for high schoolers and 200 for elementary / middle schoolers
    • Though it seems like growth is measured across multiple grades / years according to the following:
      • "Growth in ELA is the relative calculation of student progress in ELA over time as compared to their peers."
      • "Growth data are available for students in grades 4-8 and 11, with grade 3 assessment results serving as a baseline for growth measures."
    • Though, if it's measured across grades 4-11 this wouldn't really be including any students that dropped out in the middle
    • Partly based off DCAS and Smarter Balance tests??
      • I forget if the tests are different across grades or how that works
  • Basically, this dataset was not what I thought it was.
  • I don't particularly think I can get a handle on what the averages / measurements mean enough to make a good interpretation
